    {
      "term": "Statutory Regulations",
      "simpleDefinition": "Laws passed by Parliament that are mandatory and legally enforceable.",
      "anchor": "The law of the land.",
      "misconception": "Thinking 'statutory' just means 'important' rather than a legal requirement that can lead to prosecution."
    },
    {
      "term": "Non-statutory Regulations",
      "simpleDefinition": "Guidance documents and codes of practice that describe industry best practice.",
      "anchor": "Best practice guidance.",
      "misconception": "Believing these are 'optional' and can be ignored; they are often used in court to judge if you worked safely."
    },
    {
      "term": "HASAWA (Health and Safety at Work Act)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The main piece of UK legislation covering health and safety in every workplace.",
      "anchor": "The umbrella law for safety.",
      "misconception": "Thinking it only applies to the boss; it places legal duties on every employee too."
    },
    {
      "term": "EAWR (Electricity at Work Regulations)",
      "simpleDefinition": "Statutory laws specifically designed to prevent death or injury from electrical causes.",
      "anchor": "The law for electrical safety.",
      "misconception": "Confusing these legal requirements with the technical rules found in BS 7671."
    },
    {
      "term": "BS 7671",
      "simpleDefinition": "The UK national standard for electrical installations, also known as the IET Wiring Regulations.",
      "anchor": "The electrician's bible.",
      "misconception": "Believing BS 7671 is a statutory law; it is actually non-statutory guidance."
    },
    {
      "term": "On-Site Guide",
      "simpleDefinition": "A non-statutory handbook that provides a simplified version of BS 7671 for common installation work.",
      "anchor": "The pocket-sized guide to the regs.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the On-Site Guide contains every rule; it only covers standard installations up to 100 Amps."
    },
    {
      "term": "Guidance Notes",
      "simpleDefinition": "A series of non-statutory books that provide in-depth technical detail on specific parts of BS 7671.",
      "anchor": "Deep-dive technical manuals.",
      "misconception": "Thinking these are laws; they are expert explanations to help you comply with the law."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Statutory means it is the law.",
    "Non-statutory is how we prove we followed the law.",
    "BS 7671 is non-statutory guidance.",
    "EAWR is a statutory requirement.",
    "Acts and Regulations are statutory; Guides and Standards are non-statutory."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "BS 7671 is a law.",
    "Non-statutory documents can be ignored without risk.",
    "Any document with the word 'Regulations' in the title is automatically a law.",
    "The On-Site Guide is a statutory document."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Defining Statutory Regulations",
      "objective": "Define what makes a regulation 'statutory' in the UK legal framework.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In the UK electrical industry, 'Statutory' means the document is the law of the land. These are Acts of Parliament or Regulations created under those Acts. Because they are legal requirements, they are mandatory; you do not have a choice whether to follow them. If an electrician fails to comply with a statutory regulation, they are committing a criminal offence. This can lead to prosecution in a court of law, resulting in heavy fines or even imprisonment. Think of statutory regulations as the 'must-do' rules that ensure public and worker safety. They provide the legal framework that everyone in the industry must operate within to avoid criminal liability. Breaking these rules is not just a technical mistake; it is a breach of the law."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about whether a document is an 'Act' passed by Parliament or just a helpful guide."
    },
    {
      "title": "Defining Non-Statutory Regulations",
      "objective": "Define the role of non-statutory regulations and guidance.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Non-statutory documents are not laws passed by Parliament. Instead, they are codes of practice, standards, or guidance notes. While they aren't 'the law' themselves, they represent 'best practice'—the industry-agreed way to work safely and effectively. You might wonder why we follow them if they aren't laws. The reason is that if you are ever taken to court for a safety violation, a judge will look at these non-statutory documents to see if you acted competently. Following these standards is the primary way an electrician proves they have met their legal (statutory) obligations. They are the technical 'how-to' guides for the industry. They provide the specific details that the broader laws often leave out."
      ],
      "hint": "These documents are 'best practice' guides used to prove you are working to a safe standard."
    },
    {
      "title": "The Statutory List",
      "objective": "Identify specific statutory regulations relevant to electrical work.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "There are several specific statutory regulations you must recognise. The Health and Safety at Work Act (HASAWA) is the main 'umbrella' law for all workplace safety. Underneath this, the Electricity at Work Regulations (EAWR) is the most critical law for our trade, as it focuses specifically on preventing electrical injury. Other key laws include the Electricity Safety, Quality and Continuity Regulations (ESQCR), which deals with the supply network, and the Provision and Use of Work Equipment Regulations (PUWER). We also have COSHH (Control of Substances Hazardous to Health) for dangerous chemicals, CDM (Construction Design and Management) for site projects, and the PPE (Personal Protective Equipment) regulations which mandate safety gear like boots and goggles."
      ],
      "hint": "Look for acronyms like EAWR and HASAWA which represent mandatory legal Acts and Regulations."
    },
    {
      "title": "The Non-Statutory List",
      "objective": "Identify specific non-statutory regulations and guidance documents.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "The most famous non-statutory document is BS 7671, also known as the IET Wiring Regulations. Even though it has 'Regulations' in the title, it is a British Standard (BS), not a law. It is the 'electrician's bible' for how to design and install systems. To make BS 7671 easier to use on a job site, we use the On-Site Guide, which is a simplified, pocket-sized version for common installations up to 100 Amps. There are also Guidance Notes, which are a series of books providing deep-dive technical details on specific topics like testing or earthing. Finally, the Unite Union Book is another example of a non-statutory guide used by workers to understand industry standards and best practices."
      ],
      "hint": "BS 7671 and the On-Site Guide are the primary technical standards, but they are not laws."
    },
    {
      "title": "Categorisation and Identification",
      "objective": "Correctly sort regulations into statutory and non-statutory categories.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "To identify which category a document falls into, look at its title and origin. If it is an 'Act' or a 'Regulation' (like EAWR or HASAWA), it is statutory. If it is a 'Standard,' 'Guide,' or 'Note' (like BS 7671 or the On-Site Guide), it is non-statutory. A common point of confusion is BS 7671. Because people call it 'The Regs,' beginners often mistake it for a statutory law. Remember: BS 7671 is a non-statutory standard. It tells you 'how' to install safely so that you satisfy the 'legal' requirements set out in the statutory Electricity at Work Regulations (EAWR). One is the technical method (non-statutory), and the other is the legal demand (statutory). You use the non-statutory guide to comply with the statutory law."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember that BS 7671 is a technical standard (non-statutory) used to meet the legal requirements of the EAWR (statutory)."
    }
  ]
}

